              <title>What is the relationship between precision and creativity in learning design?</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/7864</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/7864</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>&ldquo;Imagination is more important than knowledge. For knowledge is limited to all we now know and understand, while imagination embraces the entire world, and all there ever will be to know and understand.&rdquo; - Albert Einstein <br /><br />As we wrote in our <a href="http://www.olds.ac.uk/blog/week3weekendround-up">weekend summary</a> (OLDS-MOOC week 3), we have been struck by the creative response to the tools we have offered up this week and levels of enjoyment some of you have expressed in using them. One of the messages that has come out loud and clear from our own research is that staff involved in the curriculum design process in institutional settings do not generally find the process very creative, and they feel that their ideas get tied down too early. We'd argue that from a learning design perspective, the balance and tension between creativity and precision is an important one. Where do you sit on this? Is creativity actually more important than precision? What is the relationship between precision and creativity?</p>]]></description>
