              <title>What makes for good design?</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2199</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2199</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>Here are my<a href="../view/2198"> top tips for design</a>, what are yours?</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Wed, 02 Sep 2009 13:27:04 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Resource: Seven top tips for designs</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2198</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2198</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p class="MsoNormal">Here<a href="http://www.slideshare.net/grainne/top-design-tips"> </a>are my suggested seven top tips for effective design:</p>
<ol>
<li>Learning activities and assignments mapped to learning outcomes</li>
<li>Appropriate mix of types of tasks (assimilative, information handling, communicative, productive, experiential, simulation)</li>
<li>Appropriate (and timely) tutor support</li>
<li>Appropriate use (and good blend) of technologies</li>
<li>Alignment with current subject (and professional) domain trends</li>
<li>Promotes good pedagogy (active learning, inquiry learning, problem-based learning, constructivist approaches, reflective, dialogic)</li>
<li>Strategic and effective design process [4 aspects: context, tools/resources, pedagogy, tasks]</li>
</ol> 
<ul>
<li>What are your views on these? </li>
<li>How could these be used?</li>
<li>Has anyone got any other suggestions?</li>
</ul>]]></description>
